WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.280
Hi, I'm Mina Chetinkar-Randell. I'm a professor at Duke University and a developer educator

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:15.800
at Posit. This year at Posit.conf, I'm teaching a one-day Teaching Data Science Masterclass.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:20.240
I've been teaching data science with R for over a decade, and I can't wait to share everything

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:25.240
I've learned over this time about successful data science pedagogy, teaching with authentic

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:30.440
tools, and doing so effectively and efficiently. Here are the top three reasons why you should

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:35.240
take this workshop. First reason is keeping up with the evolving

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:40.040
data science ecosystem is not trivial. Keeping up with it and deciding whether it's the right

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:45.520
time to update your curriculum to incorporate new tools or new features of existing tools,

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:51.520
new data sources, or new workflows, and doing so while concurrently teaching can be overwhelming.

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:55.759
This workshop is designed to share with you what's new in the land of teaching data science

00:00:55.759 --> 00:01:00.720
with R and to distill for you how you can implement these updates in your curricula.

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:05.940
Second, successful teaching doesn't end with successful curriculum design. The computational

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:10.320
infrastructure you use for your teaching is an equally important part of a successful

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:15.599
data science course, particularly if your definition of success takes into consideration

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:20.239
the experience and enjoyment of your students as well as of yourself. In this workshop,

00:01:20.239 --> 00:01:24.080
we'll talk quite a bit about how to set up computational teaching environments with Posit

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:29.519
Cloud as well as other server-based tools, how to use Git and GitHub for version control,

00:01:29.519 --> 00:01:34.160
collaboration, and as your course management system, and how to teach reproducible authoring

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:39.239
with Corto as well as how to use it to build your course materials and sites.

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:43.839
And third, this workshop will supercharge your learning and teaching prep. In one day

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:48.160
of the workshop, you will pick up a wealth of information and tips that can save you

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.959
weeks and months of trial and error on your own. Additionally, you'll meet a community of

00:01:52.959 --> 00:01:57.279
like-minded data science educators with whom you can stay in touch beyond the conference.

00:01:57.919 --> 00:02:02.959
One final comment is that this year the teaching data science workshop is offered as a one-day

00:02:02.959 --> 00:02:07.839
workshop, which means you can focus on your teaching on one of the workshop days and spend

00:02:07.839 --> 00:02:11.839
the other day learning something you've been hoping to make time for all year.

00:02:11.839 --> 00:02:17.039
Go to posit.com slash conference to register for this workshop as well as to find out about

00:02:17.039 --> 00:02:21.440
all of the other fantastic workshops we're offering at posit.com this year.

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:28.080
Looking forward to seeing you in Chicago in September!

